Data

For this assignment, we will use data from a study on vertebrate community composition and impacts from defaunation in Gabon, Africa. One thing to notice is that the data include 24 separate transects. Each transect represents a path through different forest management areas.

Reference: Koerner SE, Poulsen JR, Blanchard EJ, Okouyi J, Clark CJ. Vertebrate community composition and diversity declines along a defaunation gradient radiating from rural villages in Gabon. Journal of Applied Ecology. 2016. A description of the variables is included inside the data folder.

1. Load IvindoData_DryadVersion.csv and store it as a new object called gabon.

gabon <- read.csv("data/IvindoData_DryadVersion.csv")

5. Make a plot that shows the number of transects for each land use type.

gabon %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=land_use))+
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(fill = land_use))+
  labs(title="the number of transects for each land use type")

6. How does vegetation richness compare among land use types?

gabon %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=land_use, y=veg_rich))+
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(fill=land_use))+
  labs(title="vegetation richness compare among land use types")

7. For which land use type (national parks, logging, or neither) is average all species diversity the greatest?

names(gabon)
##  [1] "transect_id"              "distance"                
##  [3] "hunt_cat"                 "num_households"          
##  [5] "land_use"                 "veg_rich"                
##  [7] "veg_stems"                "veg_liana"               
##  [9] "veg_dbh"                  "veg_canopy"              
## [11] "veg_understory"           "ra_apes"                 
## [13] "ra_birds"                 "ra_elephant"             
## [15] "ra_monkeys"               "ra_rodent"               
## [17] "ra_ungulate"              "rich_all_species"        
## [19] "evenness_all_species"     "diversity_all_species"   
## [21] "rich_bird_species"        "evenness_bird_species"   
## [23] "diversity_bird_species"   "rich_mammal_species"     
## [25] "evenness_mammal_species"  "diversity_mammal_species"
gabon %>% 
  aggregate(rich_all_species ~ land_use, FUN = mean)
##   land_use rich_all_species
## 1  logging         19.61538
## 2  neither         19.25000
## 3     park         21.85714
gabon %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=land_use, y=rich_all_species))+
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(fill = land_use))+
  labs(title="land use type v.s. average all species diversity")

Answer: national parks is average all species diversity the greatest

8. Is there a relationship between vegetation richness and mammal species richness?

gabon %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=veg_rich, y=rich_mammal_species))+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = land_use))+
  geom_smooth(method = lm,se=T)+
  labs(title="land use type v.s. average all species diversity")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Answer: Yes. There is a positive relationship between vegetation richness and mammal species richness 9. Use filter to find all transects that have greater than 15 tree species or a breast height diameter between 50 and 60cm.

10.Which transects and land use types have more than 10 tree species and 10 mammal species? Use arrange() to sort by the number of tree species.

gabon %>% 
  select(transect_id, land_use, veg_rich, rich_mammal_species) %>% 
  filter(veg_rich >= 10 & rich_mammal_species>=10) %>%
